"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816877?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pepper-and-salt-216eda3f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pepper-and-salt-216eda3f<category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>仅标题内容</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>仅标题内容</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[John Kerry Tilts at Chinese Coal Plants]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国气候特使恳求北京损害其经济。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093543051178872"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093543051178872"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:33（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/john-kerry-china-climate-economy-xi-jinping-beijing-e50b9ef4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818839?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 17 日，总统气候特使约翰·克里在北京举行会议之前与中国气候特使解振华握手。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：VALERIE VOLCOVICI/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国周一表示，第二季度经济增速几乎停滞在 0.8%，但不用担心，约翰·克里就在这里。美国气候特使本周在北京告诉中国官员，他们需要效仿美国，迅速摆脱化石燃料，从而使中国经济进一步面临风险。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>克里上周表示，他将讨论削减甲烷排放和煤炭等问题。不知怎的，我们怀疑中国同行会接受克里先生的建议，尽管他们可能会尽其外交上的最大努力来迁就他。这就是他们多年来在气候问题上让世界陷入困境的方式。</p><p>中国签署了 2015 年巴黎气候协议，但该协议为北京提供了在 2030 年之前增加排放量的通行证。而这正是中国正在做的事情。根据监测《巴黎协定》各国进展情况的气候行动追踪系统，“中国在现行政策下的排放量仍然很高，而且没有迹象表明在 2030 年达到峰值时间表之前会大幅减少排放量。” <a href="https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/china/" target="_blank" class="icon none"></a></p><p>气候行动追踪报告称，2015年至2022年间，中国的温室气体排放量增加了近12%，而美国的排放量下降了约5%。 2015年至2021年（数据良好的最新一年）中国的甲烷排放量增加了约3%，而美国则减少了5%。</p><p>尤其是在中国煤炭问题上，克里将面临艰难的处境。气候行动追踪报告称，中国“2022年煤炭产量连续第二年达到创纪录水平”，并且“煤炭仍将是中国能源系统的支柱”。不是开玩笑：根据标准普尔全球商品洞察 (S&amp;P Global Commodity Insights) 的数据，2020 年至 2022 年间，中国新增约 113 吉瓦燃煤电厂。 2017 年至 2022 年间，全世界成功淘汰了约 187 吉瓦的燃煤电厂。</p><p>据追踪全球 30 兆瓦及以上燃煤发电项目的非营利组织“全球能源监测”的数据，截至 1 月，中国约有 306 个拟建、获批或在建燃煤发电站。这些发电厂建成后将发电约 366 吉瓦，约占全球正在开发的煤炭发电总量的 68%。</p><p>该非营利组织报告称，截至 4 月，中国还有 180 个新煤矿或煤矿扩建计划、批准或正在建设中。建成后，这些项目每年将产生约 6.57 亿吨的产量，并且每年可能排放多达 800 万吨的甲烷。</p><p>中国的一些燃煤电厂充当可再生能源的后备产能。但能源智库Ember在5月份<a href="https://ember-climate.org/countries-and-regions/countries/china/" target="_blank" class="icon none">指出</a>，去年煤炭发电仍占中国发电量的61%。这比 2000 年的 78% 有所下降，但中国的“电力部门排放总量比 2000 年高出五倍”。 。 。由于煤炭发电量不断增加，以满足不断飙升的电力需求，”Ember 报道称。</p><p>所有这些都表明，共产党不会以牺牲经济增长为代价来做出气候让步，你也不必相信我们的话。习近平主席在 2022 年 1 月的讲话中</p>据<a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/china/chinas-xi-says-countrys-low-carbon-push-must-guarantee-energy-food-security-2022-01-26/" target="_blank" class="icon none">路透社</a>援引官方新华社的一篇文章称，碳排放目标不应以牺牲中国人民的“正常生活”、能源或粮食安全为代价。<p></p><p>据《南华早报》援引官方媒体《人民日报》的一篇文章报道，习近平在三月份重申，碳中和目标“不能脱离实际”。 “我们不能扔掉现在养活我们的东西，而接下来养活我们的东西仍然不在我们的口袋里。”</p><p>中国预期的后疫情时代经济繁荣并未发生。今年早些时候的数据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-that-wont-go-away-in-china-high-youth-unemployment-f22e3b8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">显示</a>，五分之一的中国年轻人失业。克里可以随心所欲地实现气候目标，但北京不会冒着大规模失业的政治动荡的风险来实现排放目标，同时北美肆虐的野火抵消了任何二氧化碳减排量。</p><p>美国利益面临的风险是，拜登政府将在技术出口管制、对台武器或其他具有战略意义的事情上做出相应让步，以换取北京无意履行的气候承诺。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=10C997D5-A09B-478A-AE8E-951FD9064F30&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fjohn-kerry-china-climate-economy-xi-jinping-beijing-e50b9ef4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：2023 年 1 月 17 日，乔·拜登的总统气候特使在达沃斯世界经济论坛上发表讲话，将他应对气候变化的斗争与二战中对抗纳粹联系起来。图片：美联社/STF/法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/john-kerry-china-climate-economy-xi-jinping-beijing-e50b9ef4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/john-kerry-china-climate-economy-xi-jinping-beijing-e50b9ef4<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>活力</category><category>电力/燃气公用事业</category><category>发电</category><category>化石燃料发电</category><category>煤炭</category><category>电力公司</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>公用事业</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>排放量</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境/社会/治理</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>拜登政府</category><category>习近平</category><category>约翰·克里</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>排放量</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境的</category><category>社会的</category><category>治理</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>活力</category><category>电</category><category>天然气公用事业</category><category>发电</category><category>化石燃料发电</category><category>煤炭</category><category>电力公司</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>公用事业</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[California Democrats Split on Culture War]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>州参议院领导人希望与美国实现关系正常化，而司法部长则扩大了禁运。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093973350590964"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093973350590964"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BG857_freema_AM_20180731103058.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·弗里曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:31 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-democrats-split-on-culture-war-25d9e54a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818643?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，加利福尼亚州参议院临时议长托尼·阿特金斯（圣地亚哥民主党）（中）在萨克拉门托国会大厦与桑蒂的共和党院内领袖布赖恩·琼斯和参议员珍妮特·阮（亨廷顿海滩共和党）进行了会谈。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rich Pedroncelli/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>加利福尼亚州总检察长罗布·邦塔 (Rob Bonta) 声称自己是美国最具侵略性的文化斗士，他现在正式对美国 50 个州中的 26 个州表示谴责，并禁止国家资助前往这些受到谴责的司法管辖区的旅行。总检察长根据 2016 年一项不明智的法律行事，该法律授权他在州偏离金州法规中表达的激进社会议程时将其添加到禁止名单中。邦塔先生新出现的不宽容情绪尤其令人失望，因为其他加州政客似乎终于愿意停止发起州际取消活动。</p><p>林赛·霍尔登和玛吉·安斯特为萨克拉门托蜜蜂队<a href="https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article277332868.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">报道</a>：</p><blockquote>司法部长 Rob Bonta 周五宣布，加州将密苏里州、内布拉斯加州和怀俄明州添加到禁止公务旅行的州名单中，使总数达到 26 个……</blockquote><blockquote>州领导人将密苏里州和怀俄明州加入其中，因为新法律禁止跨性别运动员参加女子和女子运动项目。内布拉斯加州上榜是因为《让他们成长法案》，该法案禁止医疗保健提供者向 19 岁以下的任何人提供性别肯定护理。</blockquote><p>邦塔先生的工作人员中是否有人认为，谴责全国大部分地区是加州存在问题的有力证据？好消息是一些加州人确实想解决这个问题。 SacBee 记者注意到：</p><blockquote>增加旅行禁令的时间很特殊，因为废除该禁令的法案正在立法机关获得通过。圣地亚哥参议员临时议长托尼·阿特金斯 (Toni Atkins) 起草了参议院第 447 号法案以取消州限制。阿特金斯自称是女同性恋者，她认为这项禁令是出于善意，但却导致了意想不到的后果。她的法案将终止旅行禁令，并制定一项在其他州包容 LGBT 信息的计划。</blockquote><p>人们可能对这项法律是否出于善意存在分歧，但仍然承认加州的禁令适得其反。</p><p>正如本专栏之前指出的，就连旧金山监事会今年也同意与美国实现<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-close-to-normalizing-trade-with-the-united-states-801f77d9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">贸易关系正常化</a>。该市发现，尽管当地政客假装比其他司法管辖区的人更有道德很有趣，但事实证明，切断该市政府与明智管理州的供应商的联系的成本非常高。</p><p>至于加州政府的旅行禁令，它在限制沟通和合作机会方面相当有效。阿特金斯女士在三月份<a href="https://sd39.senate.ca.gov/news/20230329-senate-leader-atkins-announces-bridge-project-lift-travel-ban-create-marketing-program" target="_blank" class="icon none">的新闻稿</a>中指出：</p><blockquote>随着时间的推移，旅行禁令产生了意想不到的影响，进一步孤立了这些州的 LGBTQ+ 社区成员，并阻碍了加州人进行研究、开展业务以及与来自这些州的所有人接触。</blockquote><p>听起来不太包容，不是吗？旅行禁令并没有想象中那么有效，因为大学体育运动的资金已经说服州官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/uclas-big-ten-story-11658269450?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">允许加州大学洛杉矶分校将禁令转化为空洞的美德信号</a>，以加入十大体育会议。禁止名单中新加入了内布拉斯加州——又一个十大对手的家乡——突显了加州官场的虚伪。</p><p> ***</p><p><strong>来自蓝色州的蓝色航班</strong><br>一些加州读者可能希望加州法律禁止所有类型的政府资助的旅行以及目前接受政府资助的许多其他活动。</p><p>也许这些读者已经知道，有一群公职人员越来越多地自费离开加州——谁能责怪他们呢？</p><p> Libor Jany 和 David Zahniser 为《洛杉矶时报》 <a href="https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-07-16/top-l-a-police-union-officials-tells-cops-to-go-somewhere-that-understands-your-worth" target="_blank" class="icon none">报道</a>：</p><blockquote>上个月，随着新薪资合同的谈判陷入困境，洛杉矶警察保护联盟副总裁 Jerretta Sandoz 在 Facebook 上表达了自己的想法。</blockquote><blockquote>在一条显然后来被删除的评论中，9,000 多名洛杉矶警察局警官的工会领导人阐述了她所看到的在洛杉矶当警察的艰辛。桑多斯建议即将离职的洛杉矶警察局警官到政治领导层“理解的社区寻找工作”。你的价值。”</blockquote><blockquote>根据《泰晤士报》查看的帖子截图，她写道：“去一个尊重你所做工作的地方，你就不必乞求一份很棒的合同。” “去一个有市议会或城市经理公开承认你所做的伟大工作的地方，去一个没有两个或更多讨厌你的市议会成员的地方（毫不夸张）。”</blockquote><blockquote>这篇帖子是在洛杉矶警察局的合同于 6 月 30 日到期前几周写的，引起了部门内部一些人的关注，他们质疑为什么一名高级工会官员——不管是否发泄——会在这个时刻支持警察离开。洛杉矶警察局正在大量流失警员。上周警员人数降至 9,027 人，比 2019 年减少约 1,000 人。</blockquote><p>工会代表在合同期间可能会要求极高，但大量警员辞职是一个相当强烈的信号，表明洛杉矶警察的薪水并没有过高。 《泰晤士报》继续报道：</p><blockquote>在给《泰晤士报》的后续电子邮件中，桑多斯表示，她希望该部门做出“改进”，希望警官们选择留在洛杉矶警察局，同时补充说，“我建议警官们在选择为另一个机构工作时要评估的标准”在很多方面，警官们用来决定是否留在洛杉矶警察局的标准是相同的。”</blockquote><p>毫无疑问，许多洛杉矶人重视警察所做的工作，并希望他们做得更多。</p><p> ***</p><p><em>詹姆斯·弗里曼是<a href="https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1982163984" target="_blank" class="icon none">《成本：特朗普、中国和美国复兴》一书</a>的合著者，也是<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Borrowed-Time-Centuries-Booms-Bailouts/dp/0062669877/ref=asc_df_0062669877/?tag=hyprod-20&amp;linkCode=df0&amp;hvadid=312143020546&amp;hvpos=&amp;hvnetw=g&amp;hvrand=10412016619786864649&amp;hvpone=&amp;hvptwo=&amp;hvqmt=&amp;hvdev=c&amp;hvdvcmdl=&amp;hvlocint=&amp;hvlocphy=9003741&amp;hvtargid=pla-525185269824&amp;psc=1" target="_blank" class="icon none">《借来的时间：花旗两个世纪的繁荣、萧条和救助》一书的合著者。</a></em></p><p> ***</p><p>在<a href="https://twitter.com/FreemanWSJ" target="_blank" class="icon none">Twitter</a>上关注詹姆斯·弗里曼。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=157&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">订阅最佳网络电子邮件。</a></p><p>如需推荐商品，请发送电子邮件至 best@wsj.com。</p><p> （特雷莎·沃佐帮助编译了最佳网络。感谢托尼·利马。）</p><p> ***</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-democrats-split-on-culture-war-25d9e54a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-democrats-split-on-culture-war-25d9e54a<author><![CDATA[James Freeman]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Biden Accounting Jobs Boom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着新税收规则的出台，绿色眼罩的春天来临了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590080173156074644"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590080173156074644"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tax-accounting-jobs-boom-biden-economy-taxes-internal-revenue-service-8db189ae"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818022?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于所有应届毕业生，我们有两个词：税务会计。我们正在研究六月份的就业报告，你知道吗，税务准备和会计是拜登经济中增长最快的领域之一。</p><p>近几个月来，金融、信息和许多专业服务领域的招聘有所放缓，但会计、税务准备、簿记和工资工作类别持续强劲增长。该领域今年新增了30,800个就业岗位，自1月份以来其2.7%的增长率超过了专业商业服务业(0.9%)，甚至超过了休闲和酒店业(1%)。</p><p>到拜登总统上任时，大流行开始时失去的会计、税务和工资服务工作岗位已经恢复。自 2021 年 1 月以来，该领域已增加了 138,400 个工作岗位，而特朗普政府头两年半期间增加了约 30,100 个工作岗位。拜登总统任期内是绿色眼罩的春天。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816472?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>共和党 2017 年的改革通过取消许多抵免和逐项扣除（例如搬家费用和赡养费），简化了个人和企业税法。尽管会计师必须花时间跟上这些变化，但提交纳税申报表在大多数情况下并不那么繁重。然后是拜登政府。</p><p> 2021 年 3 月的《美国救援计划法案》包括针对健康保险、儿童、家属照顾、带薪休假和员工保留的新税收抵免或增强税收抵免。大多数但不是全部已经过期。 《降低通货膨胀法案》还增加了一系列绿色能源税收抵免，其中包括复杂的资格规则以及与工会劳工和项目地点相关的“奖金”。</p><p>不要忘记该法律对企业账面收入征收新的 15% 的最低税，并对绿色能源和其他政治优惠的投资免税。与此同时，被称为经济合作与发展组织的富裕国家俱乐部正在为跨国公司制定全球企业最低税，拜登政府正计划雇用数万名国税局特工来审计更多纳税人。</p><p>所有这些都意味着会计师的计费时间更长。在当今进步政府的时代，他们可能拥有最接近抗衰退的工作。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F7398B29-80AD-4BFD-BE1E-F1DBF1D77631&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftax-accounting-jobs-boom-biden-economy-taxes-internal-revenue-service-8db189ae&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报告：虽然蓝色州在个人收入方面遇到了麻烦。图片：美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tax-accounting-jobs-boom-biden-economy-taxes-internal-revenue-service-8db189ae</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tax-accounting-jobs-boom-biden-economy-taxes-internal-revenue-service-8db189ae<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>拜登政府</category><category>国税局</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tin-Foil Logic for Tin-Mill Tariffs]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>商务部长吉娜·雷蒙多会惩罚所有帮助俄亥俄州参议员谢罗德·布朗的美国人吗？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590088224079527624"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590088224079527624"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:20 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tin-foil-hats-for-tin-mill-tariffs-usw-retaliation-allies-ohio-brown-eea2666c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818825?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">位于克利夫兰的 Cleveland-Cliffs Inc. Cleveland Works 钢厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢克·沙勒特/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>就像对受青睐企业的补贴一样，对某种产品征收关税总是会导致政治上要求更多产品。特朗普的钢铁关税已经造成数千个就业岗位损失，但俄亥俄州钢铁制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CLF" class="company-name">克利夫兰克里夫斯</a>和美国钢铁工人联合会 (USW) 现在要求对锡厂产品征收额外关税。最好在价格飙升之前储备罐头汤。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>克利夫兰克利夫斯和 USW 一月份向商务部和美国国际贸易委员会 (ITC) 请愿，对来自八个国家的进口锡厂钢材征收 13.5% 至 294.3% 的关税。他们声称外国制造商正在以低于“公允价值”的价格向美国市场“倾销”用于罐头食品的钢材。</p><p>这是无稽之谈，他们也知道这一点。由于缺乏国内替代品，美国制罐制造商 62% 的供应依赖进口锡厂。克利夫兰克里夫斯公司和美国钢铁公司是国内仅有的两家重要制造商，但它们无法生产目前罐头和食品制造商所需的高级锡厂。</p><p> Cleveland-Cliffs 等美国钢铁制造商并没有投资专门的锡厂，而是优先考虑生产利润率更高的钢铁。因此，预计到今年年底，国内锡厂产能将比 2017 年（特朗普政府钢铁关税生效前一年）下降约 45%。</p><p>锡厂占克利夫兰克利夫斯钢铁销量的 2%。如果政府对进口产品征收高额关税，国内生产将无法满足需求。价格总是会上涨，这会增加克利夫兰克里夫斯的利润。但更高的价格将降低美国罐头和食品制造商的竞争力。</p><p>罐头食品出口将下降，而进口将增加。 Trade Partnership Worldwide 4 月份的一项研究估计，新关税将导致多达 39,780 个下游岗位流失，而锡厂生产可能仅创造 66 个新岗位。这意味着关税每创造一个就业机会，就会减少 600 个就业机会。</p><p>关税还会推高罐头食品的价格。 Juday Group 的一项分析估计，罐头食品价格将上涨 19% 至 30%。自疫情爆发以来，由于能源和锡厂钢材价格上涨，美国罐头蔬菜价格上涨了近 30%。总统不是声称关心“粮食安全”吗？</p><p>哦，关税将疏远加拿大、德国、荷兰、英国、台湾和韩国等盟友，这些国家都是关税请愿书的目标国家。他们可能会对美国出口产品征收关税进行报复。锡厂关税将使政府更难召集自由世界​​联盟来对抗中国的贸易政策。</p><p> “对盟国征收关税将与政府重建和加强与这些国家的关系以及在共同重要领域开展工作的努力不同步，”弗吉尼亚州参议员马克·沃纳和蒂姆·凯恩写信给商务部长吉娜·雷蒙多</p>7 月 6 日。政府将于 8 月 16 日做出关税决定。<p></p><p>来自两党的四十四名国会议员敦促政府拒绝关税。但克利夫兰克里夫斯和南威尔士州有俄亥俄州民主党参议员谢罗德·布朗支持，他明年将面临一场艰难的连任竞选。政府会惩罚美国人帮助一家公司和一名参议员吗？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftin-foil-hats-for-tin-mill-tariffs-usw-retaliation-allies-ohio-brown-eea2666c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady) 和丹·亨宁格 (Dan Henninger) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片来源：美联社/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tin-foil-hats-for-tin-mill-tariffs-usw-retaliation-allies-ohio-brown-eea2666c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tin-foil-hats-for-tin-mill-tariffs-usw-retaliation-allies-ohio-brown-eea2666c<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>蒂姆米尔产品</category><category>钢</category><category>锡</category><category>俄亥俄州</category><category>关税</category><category>工作</category><category>价格</category><category>金属矿石开采</category><category>黑色金属矿石开采</category><category>原生金属</category><category>黑色金属</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>采矿/采石</category><category>钢铁生产</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>吉娜雷蒙多</category><category>谢罗德·布朗</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>政府援助</category><category>补助金</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>金属矿石开采</category><category>黑色金属矿开采</category><category>原生金属</category><category>黑色金属</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category><category>矿业</category><category>采石</category><category>钢铁生产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Empty Government Buildings Galore]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>没有一个主要联邦机构的在职出席率超过 50%。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590094203005492446"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590094203005492446"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:19 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-government-buildings-empty-gao-report-office-space-remote-work-96e3c44a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818842?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>那些努力让员工回到空荡荡的办公室的经理们应该振作起来，因为情况可能会更糟。一份新的报告显示，联邦政府大楼已经达到了鬼城的水平，相比之下，企业大楼显得熙熙攘攘。这些空缺对纳税人来说可能是一种负担，也可能是一份小礼物，具体取决于各机构的反应。</p><p>美国政府问责办公室 (GAO) 上周的一份报告显示，联邦机构总部平均每周的占用率约为 20%。这一发现基于 1 月至 3 月期间对 24 个机构进行的调查。这些总部仅占联邦政府5.11亿平方英尺办公空间的一小部分，但政府问责局将它们作为代表性样本。</p><p>不同机构几乎一致的空虚是政府脱颖而出的另一个原因。接受调查的办公室最后四分之一的每周出勤率仅为区区 9%，没有一家办公室的出勤率超过 50%。与此相比，根据十字转门运营商 Kastle Systems 的数据，上个月纽约的公司办公室平均出勤率超过 50%。</p><p>美国政府问责局指出，政府在办公室空置的趋势中处于领先地位，因为许多联邦建筑早在新冠疫情爆发之前就很少使用。对于一家接受调查的机构，报告发现“如果所有指定工作人员在一天内进入大楼，仍然只能使用大楼容量的 67%。”</p><p>这些低效率使纳税人付出了代价，他们每年花费约 70 亿美元来租赁、运营和维护联邦办公空间。尽管各机构没有出于盈利动机来明智地管理空间，但最近的一项联邦法律旨在服务于这一目的。</p><p> 2016 年《联邦财产管理改革法案》要求行政部门制定并执行年度计划，以减少未使用的空间。该法律由共和党国会通过并由奥巴马总统签署，但几乎没有引发任何行动。美国政府问责局的报告称，该法律“提高了对房地产管理的关注”，但也承认“联邦机构仍然拥有不需要的空间”。</p><p>寻求小胜的众议院共和党人可能会要求管理和预算办公室执行法律，并帮助联邦机构摆脱一些额外的空间。在家工作的优点可能会引起争议，但没有必要用公共资金来资助空置的办公室。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=25232CEE-3316-437F-9EED-9F82FA7070FC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffederal-government-buildings-empty-gao-report-office-space-remote-work-96e3c44a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：但共和党中的一些人不喜欢这些选秀权。图片：Getty Images/Zuma Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-government-buildings-empty-gao-report-office-space-remote-work-96e3c44a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-government-buildings-empty-gao-report-office-space-remote-work-96e3c44a<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>高</category><category>政府问责办公室</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Affirmative Action Bred Hypocrisy and Victimhood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>最高法院的裁决给了保守派一个机会来重申他们对功绩的承诺。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590081592272110452"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590081592272110452"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">鲍比·金达尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:14 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-bred-hypocrisy-and-victimhood-merit-college-admissions-equality-82a8919c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818306?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6 月 29 日，华盛顿最高法院外的示威者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：何塞·路易斯·马加纳/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在最高法院决定废除大学招生中的平权行动后，自由派发誓要找到解决办法。保守派必须继续证明择优作为美国的逻辑组织原则。</p><p>受害者地位高于成就，导致许多人歪曲自己的种族和性别身份，以追求专业和学术职位的优势。尽管伦敦大学政治学家埃里克·考夫曼<a href="https://cspicenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BornThisWay2022-3.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">指出</a>，与这些身份相关的性行为并没有相应增加，但选择性大学的学生认同非异性恋的比例比历史或全国平均水平高出几倍。我听说精英私立高中的家长使用基因检测服务，希望找出任何有助于孩子大学申请的种族血统，也听说年轻的专业人​​士为了职业发展而错误地认定自己是双性恋。</p><p>当自由主义者面对现实时，种族和性别配额导致他们故意虚伪和复杂的合理化，因为他们的才能、兴趣和努力并不总是均匀地分布在他们肤浅且不断变化的政治化种族类别中。自由主义者已将增加多样性的呼吁转化为要求大学录取和雇主根据黑人和西班牙裔申请人在美国人口中所占比例的比例来聘用黑人和西班牙裔申请人。</p><p>自由主义者不愿承认的基于种族的方法的一些逻辑结论：应该改变移民和医学院政策，以减少印度裔美国医生和精英大学的数量，这些大学通常已经要求亚裔美国申请者获得更高的考试成绩，应该提高标准，这样亚裔美国学生和犹太学生在校园里的比例就不会过高。当被问及学生群体中意识形态多样性明显受到削弱的问题时，哈佛的一位管理人员在 2004 年向我承认，福音派父母不太可能把孩子送到那里，并声称这对孩子和学校都有好处。</p><p>在招生和聘用决策中给予少数族裔地位的特权不可避免地会带来相互竞争的受害者的等级制度。自由主义者已经不再争论哪些少数群体应该得到优惠待遇。他们现在在群体内创造差异。活动人士抱怨说，最近的黑人移民、他们的孩子以及混血儿夫妇的孩子比美国奴隶的后裔更不值得享受优惠待遇。</p><p>这场不体面的辩论提出了无法回答的问题：我们应该如何量化和比较美国奴隶制受害者和欧洲殖民统治受害者的大屠杀幸存者的祖先损失？自由主义者应该考虑的更重要的问题是：我们应该让那些没有犯下这些罪恶的人处于不利地位，而奖励那些没有遭受这些罪恶的人多久？</p><p>以功绩而非历史恩怨来组织美国社会，创造了巨大的财富和进步，使美国成为世界各地奋斗者的目的地，并成为消除继承优势的最佳解药。不懈追求美国梦的移民知道，无论种族或家族史如何，他们的孩子都可以获得无与伦比的成功。许多移民父母和其他霍雷肖·阿尔杰式的成功人士感激地提醒他们的孩子，他们的成功只能发生在美国。</p><p>面对日益激烈的国际竞争，美国绝不能放弃这一优势。具有讽刺意味的是，中国在20世纪末用功绩取代了意识形态的正确性来释放和转型其经济。邓小平认识到了美国自由派所不具备的：“当一切都按书本办事，当思想僵化，迷信盛行时，一个政党、一个国家就不可能进步。”当美国精英重写学校课程以强调系统性种族主义、受害者和性少数群体时，我们的竞争重点是数学、科学和创新。</p><p>自由主义者坚持结果平等，而不是机会平等，并发现种族主义的模式无处不在。自由派试图通过破坏择优录取措施来增加少数族裔学生就读精英大学的数量，而保守派则应通过赋予家长为孩子选择最佳 K-12 教育选择的权力，努力增加合格少数族裔申请者的数量。美国孩子的教育质量往往与他的邻居和家庭财富相关。让所有孩子获得高质量的数学、科学和人文教育是一项艰巨的工作，并且需要与教师工会较量，但这比修改少数学校的招生政策更能促进美国经济、改善少数族裔的成果并缩小不平等。学院。</p><p>美国根据种族区别对待人民的历史是一个严重的罪恶。保守派必须毫不留情地消灭它并阻止它复活。美国的理想是一个色盲、向上流动的社会，在这个社会中，所有利用自己的才能和不懈努力的人都可以在不偏不倚的情况下获得成功，最好的实现方式是奖励功绩。</p><p><em>金达尔先生曾于 2008-16 年间担任路易斯安那州州长，也是 2016 年共和党总统提名的候选人。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=4E93474F-26EA-40DC-979F-D5978E92765B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Faffirmative-action-bred-hypocrisy-and-victimhood-merit-college-admissions-equality-82a8919c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：民主党几十年前就表示，他们将独自制定针对美国黑人的政策。现在算账了。图片：美联社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-bred-hypocrisy-and-victimhood-merit-college-admissions-equality-82a8919c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-bred-hypocrisy-and-victimhood-merit-college-admissions-equality-82a8919c<category>平权行动</category><category>学生公平录取</category><category>哈佛大学</category><category>北卡罗来纳大学教堂山分校</category><category>种族主义</category><category>性别歧视</category><category>性别认同</category><category>性别认同</category><category>高等教育</category><category>大学申请</category><category>平权行动</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>少数民族</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>少数民族</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Old-Fashioned Conservatism Stirs in Spain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>中右翼的人民党提出了增长议程和一国文化信息。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590080070519060744"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590080070519060744"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joseph-c-sternberg" itemprop="url" rel="author">约瑟夫·C·斯滕伯格</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:14 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/old-fashioned-conservatism-stirs-in-spain-free-market-popular-party-vox-c3dca915"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818312?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 13 日，阿尔贝托·努涅斯·费霍在西班牙布尔戈斯向支持者致意。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片： cesar manso/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>马德里</em></p><p>一个幽灵正在欧洲徘徊，但它不是共产主义。相反，欧洲大陆正在经历保守主义的试探性复兴。西班牙将于 7 月 23 日进行投票，它可能是下一个做出当今最不寻常事情的国家：选举一个中右翼主流政党。</p><p>现任总理佩德罗·桑切斯是一名社会党人，他的政党在五月份的地方选举中惨败，这表明他的左翼政府已经失去了民众的支持，因此他宣布提前举行大选。果然，民意调查显示阿尔贝托·努涅斯·费霍领导的中右翼人民党领先，尽管差距正在缩小。这将使该党要么单独执政，要么与极右翼的 Vox 组成联合政府，其中人民党将占据主导地位。</p><p> Vox 并不是这里的真实故事，尽管由于其文化战争战略的因素，该党进入执政联盟的前景引发了国内外媒体的戏剧性表演。 Vox 反对在政府大楼上悬挂同性恋骄傲旗帜，嘲笑反对家庭暴力的法律对男性受害者存在偏见，并批评一项允许 16 岁以上个人更改法律文件以认定自己性别以外的性别的法律-如此孤单。</p><p>喧嚣太过分了。在人民党的联合政府中，民主的逻辑决定了只有那些存在更广泛共识的事情才会发生变化。同性婚姻将保持合法，而性别自我认同——社会主义政府在这方面已经远远超越了主流——可能会被取消。</p><p>无论如何，Vox 的明星地位可能正在消退。民意调查显示，该党在这次选举中赢得的席位可能少于其在 2019 年上次全国选举中赢得的 52 个席位（下议院 350 个席位）。该党在 5 月份的一些地方竞选中表现出色，有望加入联合政府一些省份的政府与人民党合作。但在之前与人民党谈判过各种形式联盟的地区，Vox 一直在努力将其有时相互矛盾的口号转化为可以通过的立法。</p><p>比 Vox 更令人惊讶的是人民党本身。欧洲各地旧有的中右翼主流政党正在分崩离析。法国和意大利已经没什么可说的了。安吉拉·默克尔(Angela Merkel)摧毁了长期以来欧洲保守主义支柱的德国基督教民主联盟，该联盟现在面临着选举复苏的漫长道路。英国疲惫不堪、随波逐流的保守党将在明年的选举中被彻底消灭。在瑞典和芬兰，中右翼政党仅作为大联盟的多数成员进行执政。</p><p>西班牙是西欧和南欧的两个例子之一，传统主流右翼正在研究如何令人信服地获胜。希腊是另一个，今年春天新民主党的基里亚科斯·米佐塔基斯(Kyriakos Mitsotakis)取得压倒性胜利。但希腊是一个特例，因为它在 2010 年之后经历了独一无二的严重经济危机。西班牙尽管存在所有问题，但仍是一个相当正常的大国。 What&#39;s the Popular Party&#39;s secret?</p><p> One element is its willingness to engage in the culture war in ways that appeal to Vox voters while remaining within the centrist mainstream of Spanish opinion. This is most evident on issues that don&#39;t register as much in the Anglosphere.</p><p> National unity is a big one, in a country with strong historical and cultural divisions between regions and a 20th-century history run through with political violence. On this point, the charge sheet against Mr. Sánchez is that he has cozied up to regional separatists, governed cooperatively with Communists—problematic in light of parts of that history—and has tried to reignite the left&#39;s grievances about the Franco dictatorship for political ends.</p><p> Former Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy of the Popular Party frustrated some of his own partisans by appearing soft on some of these issues. This demand for a one-nation alternative—and not the anti-immigrant or anti-European Union views that drive other European populist parties—is what fueled the rise of Vox in the first place.</p><p> Under Mr. Feijóo, who hails from a region (Galicia) with its own linguistic and cultural heritage, the Popular Party is trying to return to its one-nation-conservatism roots. The tone, with a capacious view of what the “nation” is, couldn&#39;t be more different from the pinched and divisive breed of “national conservatism” championed elsewhere.</p><p> Meantime, the Popular Party aims to rebuild its credibility on economics after some of the disappointments of the Rajoy era. During Mr. Rajoy&#39;s time in office, 2011-18, Madrid had to implement punishing Keynesian fiscal policies to comply with EU rules after the sovereign-debt crisis. Popular Party supporters especially bristled at the tax increases. This became the heyday of a centrist party called Cuidadanos—“citizens”—that favored a more free-market approach.</p><p> The media obsession with Vox has obscured the Popular Party&#39;s success in re-absorbing many voters from Cuidadanos thanks to a reinvigorated economic program. This includes promises of tax cuts, such as elimination of a windfall profits tax Mr. Sánchez imposed on banks and energy companies, the end of a wealth tax, and income-tax simplification for individuals.</p><p> Mr. Feijóo himself isn&#39;t precisely a Ronald Reagan or Margaret Thatcher, and economic policy hasn&#39;t emerged as a major theme of the campaign. But he seems to be heeding advisers who urge an emphasis on boosting investment and supply-side productivity, to make sure the Popular Party remains a home for free-market conservatives. It&#39;s a conspicuous contrast to the way other parties of the right have tried to shift leftward on economics to appear less threatening to voters, and then lost.</p><p> If the Popular Party performs well this weekend, it will be because it has fused a one-nation cultural message and a prosperity-focused, classically liberal economic program into a form of conservatism one used to take for granted in the West. Imagine if that old formula still turns out to be a winner.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Sternberg, a member of the Journal&#39;s editorial board, writes the Political Economics column. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fold-fashioned-conservatism-stirs-in-spain-free-market-popular-party-vox-c3dca915&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Kim Strassel, Bill McGurn, Mary O&#39;Grady and Dan Henninger. Images: AP/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/old-fashioned-conservatism-stirs-in-spain-free-market-popular-party-vox-c3dca915</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/old-fashioned-conservatism-stirs-in-spain-free-market-popular-party-vox-c3dca915<author><![CDATA[Joseph C. Sternberg]]></author><category> spanish elections</category><category> national election</category><category>西班牙</category><category>跨性别</category><category>税</category><category>lgbtqia+</category><category> income</category><category> windfall profits</category><category> wealth</category><category> separatist</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Gender Ideology Isn’t Kids’ Stuff]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Psychologically and emotionally, most aren&#39;t ready for it. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11423793958218753988804590027820638514184"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11423793958218753988804590027820638514184"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Erica Komisar</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 6:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sexual-ideology-identity-trans-gender-school-dysphoria-puberty-blocker-parent-rights-seattle-new-jersey-florida-nea-777ffa84"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816573?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A campaign is under way to introduce schoolchildren to the latest ideas about sexual orientation and “gender identity.” Pupils in New Jersey are <a href="https://newjerseymonitor.com/2022/04/14/parents-grapple-with-new-sex-education-standards-but-many-support-it/" target="_blank" class="icon none">expected</a> to understand the differences between these concepts by fifth grade. An official of the National Education Association, the largest US teachers union, <a href="https://www.dailysignal.com/2023/01/31/exclusive-lessons-in-preferred-pronouns-should-start-in-pre-k-largest-teachers-union-says/" target="_blank" class="icon none">recommends</a> asking preschoolers their “preferred pronouns.” The NEA&#39;s Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer+ Caucus has a <a href="https://www.nea-lgbtqc.org/documents/misc/LGBTQ%20age-appropriate%20book-list.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">reading list</a> for elementary-school children that includes titles such as “My Princess Boy” and “Jacob&#39;s New Dress.”</p><p> It&#39;s important that children learn to accept differences; but indoctrinating them or promoting an agenda is another matter. Parents, many of whom find such ideas objectionable or exotic, are often kept in the dark about what their children are being taught, or told they have no right to opt out if they are informed. Parents around the country have filed <a href="https://www.edweek.org/policy-politics/are-teachers-obliged-to-tell-parents-their-child-might-be-trans-courts-may-soon-decide/2022/04" target="_blank" class="icon none">lawsuits</a> alleging that school officials withheld vital information about their own children from them.</p><p> Children develop at their own pace. Many aren&#39;t psychologically or emotionally ready to discuss or think about their “identity.” I have seen many young adolescents overwhelmed by the need to know “who and what I am” in a heated and socially pressured environment. I have even had teen patients tell me that “identifying as heteronormative”—yes, they&#39;ve been trained to talk that way—is stressful in an environment that idealizes being “queer.”</p><p> Preadolescent children are only beginning to discover who they are. All children (adults too) have both masculine and feminine parts of their personalities, which they should be free to explore in play. If a girl doesn&#39;t like wearing dresses and a boy enjoys playing with dolls, it&#39;s cruel and destructive to lead them to believe they&#39;re actually members of the opposite sex.</p><p> The harm to children is physical as well as psychological. Medical societies and some schools promote off-label puberty blockers and life-altering surgeries for children and adolescents diagnosed with “gender dysphoria.” Seattle <a href="https://wpde.com/news/nation-world/popular-curriculum-for-4-6th-graders-covers-puberty-blockers-insists-gender-is-non-binary-flash-the-grandview-school-district-and-the-lake-washington-school-district" target="_blank" class="icon none">schools</a> teach fourth-graders that “some people decide, with the help of their doctor, to take medicine or hormones to change puberty on purpose to better match their gender.” Side effects of puberty blockers include mood disorders, brain swelling, seizures and cognitive impairment.</p><p> The Florida Legislature last year passed the Parental Rights in Education Act, which requires that classroom discussion of sexual matters be “age-appropriate” and prohibits it altogether before fourth grade. It&#39;s a good first step. Society needs to respect the role of parents and empower them to make decisions that are best for their families. For too long we have put the needs of adults over children when it comes to child care, education and safety—and now sexual ideology.</p><p> <em>Ms. Komisar is a psychoanalyst and author of “Being There: Why Prioritizing Motherhood in the First Three Years Matters” and “Chicken Little The Sky Isn&#39;t Falling: Raising Resilient Adolescents in the New Age of Anxiety.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=BE44E40A-B777-4B73-9D8E-74BFA7D27E31&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsexual-ideology-identity-trans-gender-school-dysphoria-puberty-blocker-parent-rights-seattle-new-jersey-florida-nea-777ffa84&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> As protests erupted outside a Glendale, Calif., school board meeting discussing LGBTQ+ issues in the classroom on June 6, 2023, opponents highlighted their concerns about teachers discussing sexual orientation and gender identity with children. Images: The Orange County Register via AP/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sexual-ideology-identity-trans-gender-school-dysphoria-puberty-blocker-parent-rights-seattle-new-jersey-florida-nea-777ffa84</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sexual-ideology-identity-trans-gender-school-dysphoria-puberty-blocker-parent-rights-seattle-new-jersey-florida-nea-777ffa84<category> gender identity</category><category>跨性别</category><category>性别酷儿</category><category>lgbtqia+</category><category> parent</category><category> school</category><category>心理学</category><category>精神健康</category><category>发展</category><category>父母权利</category><category>nea</category><category>新泽西州</category><category>seattle</category><category> puberty blockers</category><category> florida</category><category> gender dysphoria</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Parenting/Parenthood</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>性欲</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>养育子女</category><category>为人父母</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>性欲</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘No Labels’ Equals Trump?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A third party calling itself an &#39;insurance policy&#39; won&#39;t exactly stir voter passions. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590094124221912624"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590094124221912624"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mcgurn"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI560_mcgurn_AM_20180807122138.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mcgurn" itemprop="url" rel="author">William McGurn</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 6:12 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-equals-trump-manchin-lieberman-2024-election-biden-rematch-55feda8e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818611?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Joe Lieberman and Jon Huntsman speak at an event in Washington, Dec. 5, 2016.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Paul Morigi/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> It&#39;s probably not a good sign when a political party tells voters that it will stand down if it looks likely to make a difference in the outcome of an election. But that&#39;s what No Labels founding chairman Joe Lieberman did this weekend on ABC&#39;s “This Week.” Mr. Lieberman, the Democratic former senator and vice presidential candidate, spoke on the eve of a town hall meeting at St. Anselm&#39;s College in New Hampshire—a popular venue in an early primary state.</p><p> “We&#39;re not in this to be spoilers,” Mr. Lieberman said. “If the polling next year shows, after the two parties have chosen their nominees, that in fact we will help elect one or another candidate, we&#39;re not going to get involved.”</p><p> It&#39;s an odd statement of purpose. Then again, this is a party that believes that the way to inspire voters is to call itself an “insurance policy.” The No Labels argument is that America deserves a better choice than <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> .</p><p>但是，这是什么意思？ Mr. Trump is polling at 53.8% in the Real Clear Politics average. If he secures the GOP nomination, it will be because Republican voters chose him.</p><p> Ditto for Mr. Biden. He&#39;ll be his party&#39;s nominee if he succeeds in getting more votes than other Democrats. It isn&#39;t Mr. Biden&#39;s fault that the only ones willing to take him on are gadflies such as Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and Marianne Williamson. If heavyweight Democratic governors such as Gavin Newsom and Gretchen Whitmer don&#39;t get in, that&#39;s on them. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Main Street</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ongoing-investigation-dodge-hunter-biden-david-weiss-bribe-question-informant-67c31868?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">The &#39;Ongoing Investigation&#39; Dodge on Hunter Biden</a> <span class="date">July 10, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-who-killed-affirmative-action-ed-blum-sffa-harvard-court-race-36143530?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Edward Blum, the Man Who Killed Affirmative Action</a> <span class="date">July 3, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-bidens-malarkey-defense-hunter-taxes-fraud-gun-charge-whistleblower-bribery-fbi-6ffa15e0?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Joe Biden&#39;s &#39;Malarkey&#39; Defense of Hunter</a> <span class="date">June 26, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> In presidential races, third parties typically represent some overriding principle, such as libertarianism or green ideology, that supporters believe is insufficiently represented. In 1992 H. Ross Perot ran on a populist platform of economic nationalism and received almost 19% of the total vote. But when a third party&#39;s defining issue is that is it too good for the matchup produced by the other two parties&#39; voters—in this case, Trump vs. Biden— it can look like virtue signaling.</p><p> No Labels points to polls showing Americans also prefer a different choice. The problem is that what many of these people really don&#39;t like is the other party&#39;s candidate.</p><p> For example, a Republican primary voter may prefer <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> or Nikki Haley over Mr. Trump. But what that voter may really object to is the possibility that putting Mr. Trump on the ticket may help re-elect President Biden to a second term. Such a voter is almost certain to pull the lever for Mr. Trump in a general election.</p><p> The same is true of Democrats. An AP poll of Democratic voters in April found that fewer than half (47%) want Mr. Biden to run again in 2024. But 81% of these same Democrats say they will vote for him if he becomes their party&#39;s nominee.</p><p> Insurance policies are a hard sell here. Nonetheless, No Labels tried on Monday with its town hall featuring not only former politicians like Mr. Lieberman but also incumbent West Virginia Sen. Joe Manchin—a Democrat at odds with the leftward lurch of his party. Mr. Manchin is often thought the ideal candidate for the top of a No Labels presidential ticket.</p><p> But Mr. Manchin also embodies the No Labels dilemma. Although he has been a thorn in the side of his party, among his own West Virginia voters he is known as the man who caved when he was most needed. His vote last year saved President Biden&#39;s $700 billion Inflation Reduction Act and hurt him with his state&#39;s voters. Mr. Manchin, whose current term ends in 2024, is also trailing in the polls against his likely Republican opponent for re-election, former West Virginia Gov. Jim Justice.</p><p> In New Hampshire the No Labels leaders also talked up their new policy booklet, “Common Sense.” Named after the fiery Thomas Paine pamphlet that helped ignite the Revolutionary War, “Common Sense” is about what you would expect from those selling an insurance policy.</p><p> In other words, there&#39;s something for everyone. Except the passion of Paine&#39;s original. Oh, for one sentence like this: “But where says some is the King of America? I&#39;ll tell you Friend, he reigns above, and doth not make havoc of mankind like the Royal Brute of Britain.”</p><p> By contrast, the new “Common Sense” hails “the passage of historic bipartisan legislation like the 2021 Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act” as an example of what can be accomplished.</p><p> Still, with all its outward obstacles and inward contradictions, the No Labels movement has achieved one significant victory. Ironically, it&#39;s a highly partisan one. The new party is loathed by all the Never Trumpers—from Lincoln Project co-founder Rick Wilson to former Obama strategist David Axelrod. They see a third-party challenge taking more votes away from Mr. Biden than Mr. Trump. They&#39;re probably right.</p><p> But it&#39;s a free country. If No Labels wants to put forward a candidate despite the odds, it is free to do so. The real lesson here is that parties don&#39;t get to choose the <em>other</em> party&#39;s candidate.</p><p> <em>Write to mcgurn@wsj.com</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B8964F58-095C-4932-AB1E-4E5335D914B0&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fno-labels-equals-trump-manchin-lieberman-2024-election-biden-rematch-55feda8e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: Paul Gigot interviews Doug Schoen. Images: Getty Images/CNP/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-equals-trump-manchin-lieberman-2024-election-biden-rematch-55feda8e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-equals-trump-manchin-lieberman-2024-election-biden-rematch-55feda8e<author><![CDATA[William McGurn]]></author><category> no labels</category><category>第三者</category><category>选举</category><category>2024</category><category>基本的</category><category>复赛</category><category>全民选举</category><category>west virginia</category><category>独立的</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Theoderic the Great’ Review: The Warrior King]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>狄奥多里克的权力源于他在战斗中的成功。他徒手杀死了一位国王，并用剑将另一位对手切成两半。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818743?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">狄奥多里克大帝，东哥特人国王。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德阿戈斯蒂尼来自盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">凯尔·哈珀</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:10 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果有一个罗马版的《1066 and All That》（这部讽刺英国历史的作品），那么 476 年肯定会成为我们集体历史想象中那些可疑的大胆线条之一。就在那时，罗马最后一位皇帝罗穆卢斯·奥古斯都鲁在西方被废黜。在他十个月的统治期间，一方面是古代。另一方面，中世纪。</p><p>那么，从 493 年统治意大利直至 526 年去世的东哥特国王狄奥多里克大帝又将何去何从呢？在这位讲哥特语的武士的统治下，斗兽场仍然充斥着观众的喧嚣，清脆的山水仍然流过渡槽，卡西奥多罗斯和波爱提乌斯等拉丁文学巨擘仍然在元老院任职。</p><p>汉斯·乌尔里希·维默的《狄奥多里克大帝：哥特人之王，罗马人的统治者》是对这位杰出领袖的生活和时代的不朽探索。这是自威廉·恩斯林 (Wilhelm Ensslin) 1947 年传记以来对其主题最重要的论述，而且由于维默先生的书（此处为约翰·诺埃尔·狄龙 (John Noël Dillon) 流畅的英文译本）在广度和复杂性方面超越了前作，因此作者可以荣获最佳著作奖。我们有狄奥多里克的简介。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a1de8862-2513-4f6a-a639-1ba2a75ef33f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>狄奥多里克的故事是史诗般的，也是不可思议的。他于 453 年或 454 年出生在争议不断的多瑙河边境地区（可能位于现在的奥地利东部），父亲是一位精锐的哥特战士，母亲的背景却默默无闻。阿提拉最近去世后，狄奥多里克所属的哥特部落刚刚摆脱匈奴人的长期统治。 461 年，男孩狄奥多里克被运送到君士坦丁堡作为条约的保险。他在罗马帝国的大都市度过了近十年的青少年时期。</p><p>维默强调，狄奥多里克的权力与其说是源自他显赫的血统，也不是源自哥特式对王室合法性的尊重，而是源自他作为一名战士的成功。作为一个暴发户王子，他亲手杀死了萨尔马提亚国王巴拜。作为一支可怕的哥特军队的指挥官，他被证明是东罗马帝国善变的盟友，而东罗马帝国的皇帝本身并不是忠诚的典范。 480年代初期，他被罗马人任命为总司令。几年之内，他就围攻君士坦丁堡。</p><p>如果他的职业生涯就此结束，狄奥多里克的名字将属于动荡不安的五世纪杰出的雇佣军军阀之一。但命运眷顾勇敢者，狄奥多里克还有更远大的抱负。 488 年，他与大约 100,000 名追随者（男人、女人和儿童）一起乘坐武装车队出发，从多瑙河沿岸（位于现在的保加利亚）前往意大利，踏上一段充满不确定性的旅程。他们的目标是推翻罗穆卢斯·奥古斯特鲁斯的废黜者奥多亚塞，并为自己找到一个永久的家。狄奥多里克将奥多亚塞和他的军队逼入了拉文纳的主要据点，两人签署了一份旨在分享权力的条约。该条约持续了大约 10 天，之后狄奥多里克亲手将他的对手劈成两半（维默先生告诉我们，“用一剑，将他从锁骨到臀部切开”）。从这样的血腥开始，意大利出现了一代和平。</p><p>维默先生的调查之所以如此丰富，是因为他对古代黄昏研究的掌握。狄奥多里克的统治几乎切入了这一时期学者之间每一次重大辩论的核心。他笔下的东哥特人本质上是日耳曼部落，还是种族身份是一个被偶然的权力动态重新配置的虚构？</p><p>对于埃尔兰根-纽伦堡大学古代史教授维默来说，东哥特人是一个“暴力社会”，其物质基础是战争和掠夺。但作者认识到，追随狄奥多里克踏上意大利冒险之旅的群众是一群拥有共同历史和文化的民族，这使他们与意大利当地人区别开来，并拉近了他们与其他群体的距离，例如定居在西班牙和高卢的西哥特人。 。</p><p>维默先生对狄奥多里克国内外政策的主线的阐述令人信服。在国内，狄奥多里克追求哥特人和罗马人之间的功能专业化。前者是战士（如果也是地主），后者是平民。双轨政府反映了这种基本的分工。狄奥多里克寻求互补，而不是融合。</p><p>在国外，他寻求东罗马首都的合法性以及后罗马西部的稳定。通过战略条约和汪达尔人、西哥特人、法兰克人、勃艮第人和其他人之间惊人的联姻联盟网络，狄奥多里克成为君士坦丁堡以西最强大的统治者。由于机会主义的扩张，他控制了巴尔干半岛的大片地区、高卢南部的大部分地区和（名义上的）伊比利亚半岛。在六世纪初，法兰克王国是否会变得更加持久和重要并不明显。</p><p>如果说这本书有一个弱点的话，那就是试图解释狄奥多里克的成就如何如此迅速而彻底地解开的谜团。维默先生很好地描述了动荡的最后几年，包括在狄奥多里克的命令下处决波伊提乌斯的永恒污点。但关于狄奥多里克统治的后果却太少了。一场继承危机，然后被查士丁尼重新征服，接着是黑死病的毁灭性到来（维默先生低估了这一点），使东哥特人的实验结束了不光彩的结局。众所周知，在意大利的考古记录中，哥特式存在的物质痕迹很少。哥特人的彻底消亡和相对隐匿与一代人之后到来的伦巴第人形成鲜明对比。他们用武力从罗马人手中夺取了意大利半岛的大部分地区，并统治了两个世纪——没有一个像狄奥多里克一半伟大的领导人。</p><p>通过某种阴暗的过程，狄奥多里克的记忆在伯尔尼的迪特里希的传说中被保留或扭曲。再后来，他的遗产成为现代德国身份观念的密码。但在维默先生冷静的传记中，我们有机会看到一个不容易符合古代或中世纪简单概念的人和时刻。</p><p><em>哈珀先生是俄克拉荷马大学教授，也是圣达菲研究所分形学院的成员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>